{"type":"message","id":"8390dbff","parentId":"c10f66e7","timestamp":"2026-03-07T02:17:34.172Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the session JSONL has `memory-dir-main-2` baked into the message history. This means that when the gateway resolves the tool definitions for each turn, it's reading from the baked session state. But wait - the `memory_search` tool is called with the collection name embedded in the tool call. Let me think about this.\n\nActually, looking at the OpenClaw code earlier, the `memory_search` tool call is handled by the gateway which constructs the `qmd search ... -c memory-dir-main-2` command. The gateway resolves the collection name when setting up the memory search subsystem, and the collection name `memory-dir-main-2` was what it resolved when this session started (because at that point, `memory-dir-main` was already in QMD via my earlier rename, so `ensureUniqueName` gave it `-2`).\n \nSo the root issue is that OpenClaw assigns collection names at session start time by checking what's already taken in QMD and appending a suffix if needed. Since `memory-dir-main` was already claimed when this session (0550e6b8) started, it got `memory-dir-main-2`. The fix would be to start a fresh session, which would resolve to `memory-dir-main` since it's now available.\n\nBut wait—I'm second-guessing myself on how `ensureUniqueName` actually works. If OpenClaw creates a collection during the index operation and QMD already has `memory-dir-main` from my rename, it shouldn't create a duplicate. Let me trace through the `resolveDefaultCollections` code more carefully to understand what's really happening here.\n\nThe function maps over entries and calls `ensureUniqueName` with the base name and the existing collection names from QMD. Since `memory-dir-main` is already registered, it would increment to `memory-dir-main-2`. The real solution is to remove `memory-dir-main` from QMD entirely so OpenClaw can register it fresh when it starts up.\n\nBut I'm realizing the session JSONL has `-2` baked into it already. If the gateway reads the collection name from the session state rather than resolving it dynamically, then removing and re-registering won't help—I'd need a new session. The `memory_search` tool in the gateway uses whatever collection name is stored in the session config, so the stale reference persists.\n\nLet me trace through what actually happens when `memory_search` runs: the agent makes the call, the gateway intercepts it and executes `qmd search` with the collection name from its cached config, then returns the result. If the gateway is caching the collection name instead of looking it up fresh each time, then removing `memory-dir-main` won't fix anything. I should check if there's a per-agent state file that stores these resolved collection names.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_015w72UVtrjEaESaHS8fSqJC","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find ~/.openclaw/agents/main -name \"*.json\" | xargs grep -l \"memory-dir\" 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","usage":{"input":1,"output":1248,"cacheRead":48295,"cacheWrite":230,"totalTokens":49774,"cost":{"input":0.000003,"output":0.01872,"cacheRead":0.0144885,"cacheWrite":0.0008625,"total":0.034074}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772849832326}}
