{"type":"message","id":"39018f48","parentId":"e35751ca","timestamp":"2026-03-07T02:21:02.591Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still `-2`. The gateway is STILL using `memory-dir-main-2` despite pid 5745. This is very strange. The gateway at pid 5745 starts fresh but somehow still resolves to `memory-dir-main-2`.\n\nWait - let me think about the `ensureUniqueName` function again. It checks `existing` collections. The `existing` set is populated from QMD at startup. At this point:\n- QMD has: `memory-root-main`, `memory-alt-main`, `memory-dir-main`, `workspace-main`\n\nIf `existing` starts as a set of already-known names, and the gateway tries to create `memory-dir-main`, it finds it's already there... and increments.\n\n\nSo the real issue is that OpenClaw's `ensureUniqueName` sees the existing `memory-dir-main` collection in QMD and treats it as a conflict, forcing it to create `memory-dir-main-2` instead of recognizing it as the collection it should be using. The solution might be to remove `memory-dir-main` from the QMD `index.yml` file and let OpenClaw create it fresh.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the `index.yml` is QMD's config for persistent collections, and OpenClaw likely adds its own collections dynamically through `qmd collection add` calls, which then get written to `index.yml`. So the `memory-dir-main` entry was probably added by OpenClaw in a previous run. The problem is the sequence: Gateway starts, OpenClaw lists existing QMD collections and finds `memory-dir-main`, then `ensureUniqueName` treats it as taken and assigns `memory-dir-main-2` instead.\n\nThe real fix is that `qmd collection remove` needs to clean up both the SQLite database and the `index.yml` file so the old collection doesn't show up in the list anymore.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_013jTCtW62ueUDMRMaXAB2Fw","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/Users/aiagnet/.openclaw/agents/main/qmd/xdg-config/qmd/index.yml"}}],"api":"anth